<h2>Expert Tips</h2>
<ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-4 text-gray-700">
  <li><strong>Master the Left Bank vs. Right Bank Selection</strong> - The best Bordeaux wines showcase distinct terroir differences. Left Bank estates like Lafite, Latour, and Margaux excel in Cabernet Sauvignon-dominant blends from gravelly soils, delivering structured, age-worthy wines with cassis and graphite notes. Right Bank superstars like Le Pin and Pétrus emphasize Merlot on clay-limestone soils, producing more approachable wines with plush texture and dark fruit intensity. Choose Left Bank for formal occasions requiring structure, Right Bank for immediate pleasure and food pairing versatility.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Serve at Precisely 65-68°F for Optimal Expression</strong> - Premium Bordeaux requires cooler serving temperatures than most reds. At 65-68°F, the wine's complex tannin structure remains intact while allowing volatile compounds to express the signature cedar, tobacco, and dark fruit aromatics. Serving too warm (above 70°F) makes alcohol prominent and masks Bordeaux's elegant mineral backbone. Use a wine thermometer or cellar the bottles in a 55°F environment and allow 10-15 minutes of warming before service.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Decant Young Bordeaux 2-4 Hours, Mature Wines 30 Minutes Maximum</strong> - Bordeaux under 10 years benefits from extended decanting to soften aggressive tannins and integrate oak. Wines from powerhouse vintages like 2009, 2010, or 2016 need 3-4 hours to reach peak expression. However, mature Bordeaux (15+ years) requires gentle handling—decant only 30 minutes before service to preserve delicate tertiary aromatics like leather, forest floor, and truffle that dissipate quickly when exposed to excessive oxygen.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Use Bordeaux-Specific Glassware for Maximum Impact</strong> - The best Bordeaux wines demand large-bowled glasses with a 22-24 oz capacity. The wide surface area allows complex aromatics to develop while the tulip shape concentrates Bordeaux's signature bouquet of blackcurrant, cedar, and mineral notes. Avoid overly narrow Burgundy glasses which compress Bordeaux's structured tannins, and skip giant fishbowl glasses that dissipate the wine's concentrated aromatics too quickly.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Follow the 20-Year Rule for First Growth Aging</strong> - Premium Bordeaux from classified estates reaches peak drinkability 15-25 years after vintage, with First Growths often requiring two decades. Wines like 2000 Mouton Rothschild or 2005 Haut-Brion are just entering their optimal drinking windows now. Plan purchases accordingly—buy current releases for future enjoyment, and seek 15-20 year old bottles from strong vintages like 2000, 2005, 2009, and 2010 for immediate consumption.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Identify Peak Drinking Windows by Vintage Character</strong> - Bordeaux vintages have predictable aging curves. Powerful, tannic years (2005, 2010, 2016) need 20+ years for First Growths to soften. Elegant, earlier-drinking vintages (2001, 2004, 2014) reach maturity in 12-18 years. Hot vintages (2003, 2009) drink well young but may fade quickly after 20 years. Cool, structured years (2002, 2008) develop slowly but reward patience with extraordinary longevity.</li>
  
